Redwine Analysis

Tu Duong

Feb 19, 2018

This project explores a dataset of 1600 red wine samples to understand what physicochemical properties influence the wines quality.

Most of the wine in the sample have average quality (score 5-6)

With the histogram for each variable, we can quickly see the distributions.

Most variables are bell-shaped or left skewed.

Most samples have fixed acidity from 6-9 gram/liter, the the shape is slighty skewed to the left. There are some outlier with acidity higher than 13 gram/liter.

Volatile acidity has a bell-shape distribution, with outlier samples with acid level higher than 1 gram/liter.

Using binwidth 0.1 is does not give us a clear view on distribution. Using binwidth 0.01 reveals there are many sample with zero citric acid. It is quite rare to have citric acid level higher than 0.75g/l.

Most samples have residual sugar from 2-3grams/liter. Interesting there is no sweet wine (sugar > 45gr/liter)

Removing the outlier with sugar higher than 2g/l, it is easier to see the bell curve distribution around 2g/liter.

Chlorides has similar distribution to residual sugar, most samples has chlorides level less than 0.1g/l. Some outlier samples have chloride up to 0.6g/l. I am wondreing if those outliers has negative or positive influence to the quality of the wine, if it has any influence at all?

A zoom in to the chlorides level of the majority of the sample fluctuate around 0.75g/l.

Free surfur dioxide is mainly below 20mg/l.

Total sulfur dioxide is left skewed. Most samples have total silfur dioxide below 150mg/l.

Transform total sulfur dioxide to log scale shows a close to normal distribution.

Density follows bell curved distribution with a median of 0.9968g/cm^3.

pH distribution follow bell curve with median of 3.310.

After transfrom x axix to log10 scale, the distriubtion is bell curved. This suggests a multiplicative effect for this variable.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains about 1600 samples, each has 12 variables. All features are expressed in numbers (quality in integer, which is a categorical variable).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest is quality. We would like to know if and how much the physicochemical properties can be used to predict the quality of the wine.

The median quality is 6, wine sample quality range from 3to 8.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

All other features apart from X seems to be independent from each other and they all should be used to investigate how they influence quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No new variables are created as all influencing features seems independent from each other.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Dataset is clean so data cleaning is not required. I log transfromed the left skew variables to check if they have a clear multiplicative type.

I prepared the correlation matrix to see the relationships among various variables before selecting the important ones to continue the investigation. In particular Id like to see how physicochemical variables influence quality. I am surprised to see there is no strong colleration between quality versus the input variables. The highest correlations are with alcohol level (0.476), volatile acidity (-0.391), sulfates (0.251) and citric acid (0.226).

Although I can understand high level of volatile acidity makes the wine sour and therefore unpleasant, I never thought that alcohol level have high colleration to quality.

Now I start to wonder about the factors that can influence the wine quality that are not captured by the variables in the dataset.For example, the grape type, grape ripping level, age of the vine, or the wine region could create some charactrs that we do not capture here (I am thinking about Bordeaux and Napa Valley here).

However, there are interesting relationships among the physicochemical variables. For example, fixed acidity collerate strongly with density (0.668) and pH (-0.683), and citric acid (0.672).

I also wondered how the outliers in the physicochemical properties impact wine quality? Will they create exceptional good wine or bad wine?

My next analysis will go deep into these interesting relationships.

Overplotting problem to be fixed.

Using jitter shows an interseting insight: most of the wine with alcohol below 10% are of average quality. Higer quality wine (7 and above) have acohol level of 10% or more.

This box plot makes the relationship look clearer. The median alcohol levels of wine with quality index 7 and 8 are higher than those with lower quality.

However, there are many average quality sample with high alcohol content. What are other variables that can explain this?

Low correlation between the two variables.

Sulphates level has a lower correlation with quality. In general, the higher sulphates, the higher the wine quality - up to a point. No good wine has sulphates level above 1.5g/l.

Similar to sulphates, citric acid has a weak correlation to quality, but overall higher quality wines have higher median citric acid.

Now I look into relationships among variables other than quality. There are interesting relationship among the physicochemical variables. For example, fixed acidity collerate strongly with density (0.668), pH (-0.683), and citric acid (0.672).

There is a correlation, but there are varied level of fixed acidity with citric acid level of 0g/l,

Now I want to understand how the outliers impact quality. I dont like sweet wine, so I am checking for the sugar level outlier.

This plot indicate that good wine does not have residual sugar higher than 8g/l.

Same as residual sugar, exceptionally high chlorides does not make a good wine.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

There are weak correlation between quality and other physicochemical qualities. It seems that there are many factors could influence the quality of the wine, and perhaps the factors included in the dataset is not enough to predict the wines quality.

Having said that, there are some interesting relationships between wine quality and the physicochemical features. The strongest correlation (0.476) is with alcohol level, where the dataset suggests that high quality wine (7/8) have median alcohol level higher than 11% while low quality wine (3-5) have median alcohol content less than 11%.

On the other hand, the is a negative correlation between quality and volatile acidity. The box plot shows the higher the acidity, the lower the wine quality.

It is also interesting to note the sweet spot for sulphates. Good wines have sulphates level around 0.7-0.8g/l. Sulphates level outside this range seems to to result in bad or average wines. Similarly, the sweet spot for citric acid is around 0.3 -0.5 gram/liter.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

There are interesting relationship among the physicochemical variables. For example, fixed acidity collerate strongly with density (0.668), pH (-0.683), and citric acid (0.672) .

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Quality of wine is positively, although not strongly, correlated with alcohol content.

Now I want to quantify the relationship of various input variables with quality. I will convert to convert the factor quality into a numerical variable and run a linear regession model. The assumption that the final quality score is rounded to the nearest interger number.

Plot One

Description One

It is surprising to see there is a relationship between wine quality and its alcohol content. Median alcohol content of higer quality wine (7 and 8) is higher than 11%, while most lower wine quality have alcohol below 11%.

Plot Two

Description Two

Among the variables, alcohol content has highest correlation to wine quality. However, the plot indicated that the relationship is weak. The top 4 variables (alcohol, variable acidity, sulphates, and citric acid) can only explain one-third of the quality of redwine. THis indicates that there are many other factors that influence the wine quality that is missing from the dataset (for example, grape types or regions)

Reflection

The wine datasetcontains information on 1600 samples with 12 variable. I started by understanding the individual variables in the data set, and then I created many plots to understand the relationship among variables, most important to find out the important variables that might influence quality.

It is interesting to understand the values and distributions of the variables. The frustration startedafter I built the scatterplot matrix that shows weak correlations between quality and other variables. The multivariate analysis further confirm the hypothesis that there are might be so many factors influence wine quality, or the important factors (grape types, wine region) were not captured in the dataset. It is interesting to understant the relationship between alcohol level with with quality, as well as volatile acidity with quality. Also, it is suprising to discover that there is a high correlation among fixed acidity, citric acid, and density.

For future work related to this dataset, I would like to include additional variables that could be important in determining the quality of the wine. From my experience, the wine quality could depend on the grape variety (for example, merlot,cabernet sauvignon, shiraz, etc.), the wine region, and the year of the wine. Adding these additional variable can help us to build a better predictive model of wine quality.
